text.tspan: Peer A begins with no chunks.
Peer A says they are interested in downloading all chunks
Peer B has six chunks already in storage.
Peer B says which chunks they are interested in downloading.
Because the chunks do not form a contiguous range, three want messages are sent.
Peer B sees Peer A’s want message and replies
with the chunks they have within the wanted range.
Seeing that Peer B has chunks it wants, Peer A requests them and they are transferred.
No need for Peer A to say they have the chunks they just received, this is implied.
Later, Peer A receives more chunks from another peer in the swarm.
Because Peer B had previously wanted these chunks, Peer A
sends have messages to advertise their availability.
Peer B sees the have messages and requests the remaining chunks from Peer A.
Now both peers have all the chunks (until more are added to the end).
